# Lab Name
Reflected XSS into HTML context with most tags and attributes blocked

## Vulnerability
Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) – Reflected XSS with Partial Input Filtering

## Objective
Exploit a reflected XSS vulnerability despite restrictions on most HTML tags and attributes.

## Entry Point
Search functionality

## Exploitation Type
Reflected XSS / Filter Bypass

## Methodology
1. Open the lab and locate the search functionality

2. Test basic XSS payloads and observe that most HTML tags and attributes are blocked

3. Identify which tags and attributes are still allowed by the filter

4. Determine that the following payload bypasses the filter restrictions

5. Inject the payload into the search parameter

6. Submit the request

7. Trigger the associated event if required

8. Observe that JavaScript executes successfully

## Payload Used

<body onresize=print()>

Exploit Server

<iframe src="https://0ad600bb0452c3e0815a350c00f90084.web-security-academy.net?search=<body onresize=print()>" onload=this.style.width='100px'>

## Result
Successfully bypassed the filtering mechanism and executed arbitrary JavaScript.

## Impact
- Execution of arbitrary JavaScript
- Session hijacking
- Cookie theft
- Phishing attacks
- Account compromise

## Mitigation
- Do not rely on blacklist-based filtering
- Implement proper context-aware output encoding
- Use allowlist-based HTML sanitization
- Apply Content Security Policy (CSP)
- Validate and sanitize all user-controlled input

## Learning
Blocking only specific tags and attributes is not sufficient to prevent XSS.
Attackers can often identify alternative tags, events, or browser behaviors to bypass filters and execute JavaScript.
